[5] Cholera - Sudan (South)
Date: Wed 8 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters [edited]
<http://today.reuters.co.uk/news/newsArticle.aspx?type=healthNews&storyID=2006-
03-08T122154Z_01_MCD836134_RTRIDST_0_HEALTH-SUDAN-CHOLERA-
DC.XML&archived=False>

Sudan cholera outbreak reaches 3rd major town
-----------------------------------------------
An outbreak of cholera in Sudan's south has spread to a 3rd major
town and has claimed at least 132 lives in the war-torn area with
little clean water or sanitation, aid agencies said on Wed 8 Mar 2006.
Medecins Sans Frontieres said 12 people had tested positive for
cholera in the town of Malakal, [400] miles north of the origin
of the outbreak. Almost 6000 cases have been recorded in the southern
capital Juba and the nearby town of Yei, WHO said, adding the
outbreak had also spread to surrounding towns.
"There were 12 cases confirmed for cholera in Malakal," MSF medical
coordinator Kees Keus told Reuters.
2/3rds of south Sudan's population drinks unsafe water. After a 2005
peace deal, which ended Africa's longest civil war in Sudan's south,
hundreds of thousands of people have been returning home. "It's
difficult to prevent the spread when there are such large population
movements," Keus said.
--
